  <div class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="text-xl">☀️</span>
      The Quick Answer (Standard Depths)
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">A standard 4x8 raised bed has a surface area of **32 square feet**. The volume depends on the depth of the bed. Here is the direct answer for standard depths:</p>
    <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 font-medium">
      <li>To fill a **12-inch** deep 4x8 bed, you need **32 cubic feet** (approx 1.2 cubic yards).</li>
      <li>To fill a **6-inch** deep 4x8 bed, you need **16 cubic feet** (approx 0.6 cubic yards).</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-4"><em>(Keep in mind that soil settles by 10–15% after watering, so it’s wise to round up slightly.)</em></p>
  </div>

  <article class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-gray-700">
    
    <p>The 4x8 raised bed is the classic size for home vegetable gardening. It offers maximum growing space while allowing you to reach the center from either side without stepping on the soil. But nothing kills the excitement of building a new bed faster than having to make three extra trips to the garden center because you didn’t buy enough soil.</p>

    <p>Calculating <strong>how much soil for a 4x8 raised bed</strong> is straightforward construction math: Length &times; Width &times; Depth. However, most people run into trouble converting that volume into the bags or cubic yards sold at stores.</p>

    <p>In this guide, we will break down the exact math, provide simple cheat sheets for bag counts, and discuss when it’s cheaper to buy soil in bulk.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">Soil Volume Cheat Sheet by Depth</h2>
    <p>The table below provides the volume required for a 4x8 raised bed ($32 \text sq ft) across various common depths. It converts the total cubic feet into cubic yards and standard bag sizes. This is the simplest way to determine <strong>how much soil for a 4x8 raised bed</strong> without doing the algebra yourself.</p>

