    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">Bulk vs. Bagged Soil: What's the Better Deal?</h2>
    <p>This is the most critical decision in raised bed planning. Buying bagged soil is convenient, but the cost per cubic foot is significantly higher. The "crossover point" where bulk soil becomes cheaper is usually around **one cubic yard (27 cubic feet)**.</p>

    <p>Looking back at our 4x8 soil chart, a **12-inch deep bed** requires **1.2 cubic yards**. This puts a standard 4x8 bed right in the sweet spot for a bulk soil order.</p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5 my-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-5">
        <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2 text-base">Buying in Bags (Pros & Cons)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm list-inside list-disc text-gray-700">
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Easy to transport in any vehicle.</li>
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Easy to manage (one bag at a time).</li>
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Exact quantity known.</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> Most expensive per cubic foot.</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> significant plastic waste.</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> Requires heavy lifting of 16–22 bags.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-5">
        <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2 text-base">Buying in Bulk (Pros & Cons)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm list-inside list-disc text-gray-700">
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Cheapest option by far.</li>
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Delivery available (drops it in your driveway).</li>
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Better soil quality (local compost/topsoil blends).</li>
          <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Zero plastic waste.</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> Requires delivery fee (often $60–$100).</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> Delivery drops it in a massive pile.</li>
          <li><strong>Con:</strong> Requires wheelbarrow and shovel to move.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>The Final Recommendation:</strong> If you are filling just *one* 6-inch deep bed (8 bags), buy bags. If you are filling *one* 12-inch deep bed (16 bags) or multiple 4x8 beds, always buy in bulk from a local landscape supply company. You will get a superior compost/topsoil blend for a fraction of the cost.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">What Kind of Soil Mix Should I Use?</h2>
    <p>Do not fill your raised bed with plain native "dirt" or cheap topsoil. Topsoil in a bag is often heavy, lacks nutrients, and compacts quickly, smothering your plant roots. You need a rich, porous mixture designed specifically for raised beds.</p>

    <p>A classic, reliable blend (sometimes called "Mel's Mix") is an equal thirds approach:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>**1/3 Quality Compost:** For nutrients and organic matter (the most critical component).</li>
      <li>**1/3 Peat Moss or Coconut Coir:** For moisture retention.</li>
      <li>**1/3 Aeration:** Such as Perlite or Vermiculite, to keep the soil light and porous.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>Alternatively, many landscape supply companies sell a pre-made **"Raised Bed Mix"** in bulk, which is typically a 50/50 blend of screened topsoil and finished compost. This is an excellent foundation that can be enhanced with organic fertilizer later.</p>

